{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930103001/0246.xml":{"full_text":"ROOSEVELT SEEN\nASCERTAINVICTOR\nRepublicans as Well as Dem\nocrats, in Tammany Strong\nhold, Hold View.\n(Continued Prom First Page.)\neffect in the rest of the country. If not\nNew York.\nThese editorials have pictured Gov.\nRoosevelt as subservient to Tammany\nHall. Tuttle has charged again and\nagain that, for the support of Tammany,\nheaded by John F. Curry, the Governor\nhas failed to open up the investigation\nof alleged corruption in the greater city.\nThe administration in Washington has\ntaken cognizance of the situation and\nfirst through the Secretary of War, Mr.\nHurley, and again through th\u00bb Secretary\nof State. Mr. Stimson, has broadcast\nthe charge that Gov. Roosevelt has been\nwilling to keep hands off in the city in\norder to have the backing of Tammany,\nwithout which he could scarcely expect\nto win.\nThe cumulative effect of these on\nslaughts on Roosevelt may make it\ndifficult for him to win nomination in\nthe next Democratic National Con\nvention. The opposition will seek to\ncharacterize him as Tammany\u2019s tool.\nAnd if he should receive the Demo\ncratic nomination for President, the\nRepublican attack will be directed along\nthe same line. It does not appear\nprobable that within the next week\nAnything new will be turned up by the\nspecial grand jury or other investiga\ntors involving other members of the\nNew York City judiciary in the cor\nruption charges. But should further\nscandals develop after the expected\nelection of Gov. Roosevelt, his present\nattitude would rise up to plague him\ntwo years hence.\nTammany at present is hitting on all\neight, cylinders, John F. Curry, the\ndistrict leader, who fought his way\nto the front more than a year ago and\nsucceeded to the post held by George\nWashington Olvany, has proved an ef\nfective leader. He has been able to\nharmonize differences that existed in\nthe Democratic organization. In the\nmayoralty campaign after he took\ncharge. Mayor \u201cJimmy\u201d Walker was\nelected by nearly 500,000 votes over his\nRepublican opponent. Representative La\nGuardia. This approached the biggest\nvote by which A1 Smith ever carried\nthe city. The Tammany leader today\nis confident that the Democrats will do\nas well by Roosevelt as they did by\nWalker and by Smith in this city.\nBuilds State Organization.\n1\nGov. Roosevelt, unlike his predecessor,\nA1 Smith, has undertaken to build up\na Democratic organization up-Stafte,\nSmith\u2019s idea was that the city vote\nwould be sufficient to win for him.\nRoosevelt in the last two years has\ntraveled frequently through the State.\nHe has advocated legislation in the\ninterest of the farmers of New York.\nHe has claimed credit for work actually\nbegun by the New York Legislature,\nwhich is Republican, and has been\naccorded that credit. The consequence\nIs that Roosevelt is more popular in\nthe up-State rural sections of New\nYork than was Smith. If the poli\nticians are not mistaken, he will receive\na considerable number more votes up\nstate than did Smith.\n'\"be Democratic organization seems\nto be far better off for money this year\nthan does the Republican. The Repub\nlicans saje that it is hard to raise pioney\nfor the campaign. The Democrats are\nnot complaining. In New York City,\nwhere Tammany is working all the year\nround, the wsr chest is pretty well\nfilled.\nCharles H. Tuttle is an able man, a\nfood lawyer and proved himself an\nactive prosecutor. But, he is no rabble\nraiser. He lacks personal magnetism,\n\u2022o necessary on the stump in political\ncampaigns. If he were a Theodore\nRoosevelt or an A1 Smith, with the cor\nruption issue to hammer home, he\nmight have a chance. But it was not\nlong after he started campaigning up\nstate, early in the contest, that it be\ncame apparent that he was not \u201cclick\ning.\u201d His audiences did not warm to\nhim. They had heard of the lnquities\nof Tammany often before. Roosevelt\nwas talking about State issues and\ntaxes and water power and public utili\nties. while Tuttle was sticking to Tam\nmany.\nNo Uprising in Sight.\nIt might be supposed that in New\nYork City itself the corruption issue.\nwith charges that judgeships were sold\nby Tammany and with at least one\njudge Indicted for purchasing his job,\nwould cause an uprising of the voters.\nIf the polls taken by district leaders\nare to be believed, however, there la no\nsuch uprising In prospect. The people\ndo not appear to be particularly excited.\nAnd yet the record is an unsavory one.\nIn addition to scandals Involving\nother city officials evidence was accu\nmulating before the middle of last Sum\nmer. according to Democratic New York\nWorld, that \u201cmen of low character had\nbeen made judges by Tammany and Its\nallied organizations in the city of New\nYork. Judge Mancusco was compelled\nto resign under threat of an investiga\ntion for his removal following the scan\ndalous collapse of a bank from which\nhe drew a salary while he sat on the\nbench.\nJudge Vause was convicted in the\nFederal Court for a stock swindle and\nsentenced to six years in prison. Magi\nstrate Vitale was removed on complaint\nof the Bar Association after it had been\nshown that he had borrowed $19,000\nfrom Arnold Rothstein (a notorious\ngambler, racketeer and protector of\ncriminals, who was murdered some time\nago).\nThe final touch to the record was\nadded when evidence was produced that\nthe wife of Magistrate Ewald. an ap\npointee of Mayor Walker, had loaned\nSIO,OOO to a Tammany district leader\non an unsecured note at the time of her\nhusband's appointment. Ewald Is now\nunder Indictment.\nBut despite the record. New York\nCity does not appear to be excited. It\nlooks as though corruption Issues left\nthe voters cold. Perhaps there will be\na vote of protest that is now keeping\nsilent. Such things have happened in\nthe past. But if there is such a pro\nOpen Until 5 P.M. Oct. 31 and Nov. 3\nBefore You\n'0 Spend Is the\nINTEREST lime to u3VC\n11 paid ON To induce healthy\nBAV,NGS growth, don't let your\nACCOUNT# savings fund depend\non chance deposits;\nfwi r* but bank a definite\nIDC Columbia amount, first thing,\nt><UlK \u201cColumbia National\"\nis serving hundreds of\nbeet earnest thrift observ- i II\ners, and invites your\ndeposits.\nSurplus Q ne D o ar or More Will\nK).00 Open a Savings Account N\nI 11\nResigns, Fights Pinchot\nREPRESENTATIVE GRAHAM.\ntest vote, it is very, very silent at the\npresent time.\nThe charge against Gov. Roosevelt\nis that he has not only failed to take\nthe lead \\in bringing about complete in\nvestigation of the alleged sale of judicial\noffices, but that he has acted to post\npone or to prevent any real investiga\ntion. His statement the other night in\nNew York City that he believed the\npeople of New York City could take\ncare of their own affairs has not been\nparticularly well received, certainly by\nthe press of the city. The New York\nWorld, editorially, took a wal\nlop at the Governor, saying:\n\"If the Governor is so convinced that\nthat the seven million people of New\nYork City can handle their own affairs,\nwhy did he take the Ewald case out\nof the hands of the New York County\ndistrict, attorney and the regular coun\nty grand jury and give it to the attor\nney general and a special grand Jury?\n\"We are loath to believe this is Gov.\nRoosevelt\u2019s last word on the corruption\nissue in this city. We cannot even yet\nadmit that Tammany has him tied,\nmuzzled and blindfolded by the threat\nthat only in that ignominious state can\nhe be sure of its votes.\n\u201cIf so it prove, then the saddest\nthing in American public life today is\nthe thing politics has done to Franklin\nD. Roosevelt.\u201d\nThat is merely a sample of the com\nment made upon Gov. Roosevelt\u2019s at\ntitude by New York newspapers. But\nnotwithstanding this unfavorable com\nment, the Democratic leaders continue\nto assert that they will carry New York\nCity by half a million votes for Roose\nvelt. and some of the Republicans give\nit to him by 325,000 votes. Conservative\nobservers estimate that Roosevelt will\ncarry the State by 250,000 votes against\nTuttle, and some of the observers place\nthe Governor\u2019s lead as high as 350,000.\nBYRNS SEES POLITICS\nMOTIVE FOR RELIEF\nDemocratic Leader Says Time of\nAction on Eve of Election\nArouses Suspicion.\nRepresentative Byrm of Tennessee,\nchairman of the Democratic Congres\nsional Committee, charged that the\nadministration, In postponing its ef\nforts to relieve unemployment \u201cuntil\nthe very eve of the congressional elec\ntions, arouses the su piclon 'that Its\ninterest is as much political as it Is\nhumane.\u201d\nIn a statement through the Demo\ncratic National Committee Byrns add\ned that \"It is a matter of general\ngratification that the Federal admin\nistration has at last become aroused\nto the necessity of grappling with the\ngrave unemployment problem.\u201d\n\"While we rejoice.\u201d he said, \"that\nthe administration is at last to do\nwhat it can at this late day to ease\nthe distress from which so many mil\nlions are suffering, we cannot forget\nnor fail to hold Mr. Hoover and his\nadvisers responsible for their unpar\ndonable delay in doing anything at\naU.\u201d\nByrns added that, \u2018\u2018although the ad\nministration had from last November,\nwhen the depression became serious,\nuntil July 1, when appropriations for\nthe new fiscal year became available,\nto plan for an enlarged Federal pro\ngram of public works, it actually ap\npropriated $25,922,562 less for public\nworks this year than it did last.\u201d\nA uniformed junior police force has\nbeen formed to aid regular police in pro\ntecting school children at Seminole,\nOkla.\nIVIJ BY tA&C|t JCAIf\nB MODfcBN MtTHOM\nTkttirDoni!\nSaturday, Sunday\nand Holidaij^y^\nMONIHMG iPKIALIiIS\nBILL LYNCH'S\nAIT\u00a9 LAUNDRY,/^\n632 N.Y.Ave.,N.W.-627 fc.N.W.\nVacuum Clean inf. Ts<\nOnto Painting. >3Sy\n\u25a0fHE EVEKTN'G ST vP. v, \".0. 1930.\nGRAHAM INITIATES\nFIGHT ON PINCHOT\nRepublican Resigns Position\nto Support Hemphill in\nPennsylvania.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPHILADELPHIA, October 30\nRepresentative George S. Graham of\nPhiladelphia, has resigned as Pennsyl\nvania's member of the Republican\nCongressional Committee and announced\nthat he will support John Hemphill,\nDemocratic-Liberal candidate for Gov\nernor.\nMr. Graham, who is chairman of the\nHouse Judiciary Committee, in a formal\nstatement, said he regarded Gifford\nPinchot. Republican gubernatorial\nnominee, as a \u201cmenac- to the return\nof prosperity\u201d and added that, his elec\ntion would \"increase t.he depression and\nsuffering in business.\"\nThe Representative asserted that\nPinchot was not a Republican; that he\nwas against the program of President\nHoover and that he \u201cassociates with\nthe President's enemies in the Senate.\"\nPinchot\u2019s goal. Graham declared, \u201cis\nto wffeck the Republican party on the\npower issue raised by Senator Norris\nand. perhaps in 1932, become on some\nplatform or with some party a nominee\nfor President.\u201d\n\u201cPresident Hoover.\u201d Graham\u2019s state\nment added, \u201caccepting Mr. Pinchot\u2019s\nown confession that he is a \u2018progressive\nstraight and proposes to act with other\nprogressives\u2019 to destroy the policies of\nthe Republican party, has not offered\nhim any support, while giving it ireely\nto New York, New Jersey and other\nStates.\u201d\nMr. Pinchot replied yesterday to a\nstatement by directors of the Pennsyl\nvania Railroad denying charges alleged\nto have been made by him during the\npresent political campaign.\nMr. Pinchot, declared his attacks W\u2019ere\nnot directed against the railroad com\npany. but against Gen. W. W. Atterbury,\nits president.\nAsserting that Gen. Atterbury had\n\"misused the power of his office in a\ndisgraceful political fashion.\u201d Pinchot\ncharacterized the statement of the\nPennsylvania directors as \u201ca series of\ncarefully worded evasions,\u201d and said\n\u201csome of the assertions are so menda\ncious\u201d that he doubted whether the\ndirectors knew they were to be made.\nThe railroad\u2019s statement. Pinchot\nsaid, was \u201cbut a sample of the lengths\nto which he, Atterbury\u2019, has gone In\nhis efforts to help Hemphill.\u201d\n\nPrince Is Suicide.\nBUCHAREST, October 30 UP,.\u2014\nPrince Grlgore Cantacuzene, member\nof an old Byzantine family, committed\nsuicide yesterday. His act was charged\nto ill health.\nr i\nOhUtpsborn\nI EIXVENTII ST. BETWEEN Ft, G\njt Tomorrow brings to a close our\nenthusiastically aw'aited month end\nPairs of Regular $6.50\n$8.50 and $lO Shoes on Sale at\nBrown Suede! Blue Kid!- j\nBlack Kid! Reptile Grains!\nBrown Kid! Satina!\nBlue Suede! Patent*!\nStyles for every occasion\u2014scores of them for\nstreet, for dress\u2014Oxford. Pumps, Straps, Ties.\nAll sizes to 8, AAA to C, but not in all styles\u2014\nspike or Cuban heels.\nThese bona fide savings on fashionable shoes ends to\nmorrow night, as every pair goes back to regular higher\nselling price\u2014take advantage of them.\nFloor\n\nWASHINGTON'S FINEST MEN'S WEAR STORE\nRALEIGH HABERDASHER\n1310 F Street\nRaleigh Hats\nThe new Silver Grey is the\ncolor we feature in these luxu- f\nrious silk-lined Welt Edge and\nSnap-brim Hats you couldn\u2019t __\nbuy more for\nri _, Raleigh \u201c8\u201d Shoes\nIwm I Jfl\u00df] \u2014give you the utmost in comfort,\nthe smartest styles and the long\nest wear i n Calfskins and Mar\ntin\u2019s imported Scotchgrains, yet\nthey\u2019re only\nAUTHOR TO SPEAK\nMurdock Pemberton, author and critic\nof New York, will address members of\nthe Community Drama Guild of Wash\nington in the McKinley Auditorium.\nSecond and T streets northeast, Wed\nnesday night, November 5.\nPemberton will speak on \u201cNinety\nYears on Broadway\u201d or the \"Secret of\nProducing Plays.\u201d\nThe United States Army Band and\nMiss Lisa Gardiner and other dancers\nwill present a program.\nSMITHASKSNATION\nTO GO DEMOCRATIC\nMakes Triple Charges of Re\npublican Failure in Busi\nness Crisis.\nBy the Associated Press.\nNEW YORK, October 30. \u2014Former\nGov. Alfred E. Smith last night urged\nthe election of a Democratic Congress\nand told a Nation-wide radio audience\nhe had three charges to make against\nthe Republicans. He listed them as\nfollows:\n1. They made campaign pledges of\ncontinuing prosperity which they could\nnot redeem.\n2. They refused to face business\ncrisis until It was forced upon them.\n3. They failed to take necessary\nsteps to relieve the situation.\nAmplifying these, Mr. Smith said:\n\u201cIt is a matter of history that the\nPresident himself as short a time ago\nas March 8 made the definite state\nment that the situation would clear in\n60 days. He was assisted by his cab\ninet officers in his refusal to face the\nfacts. As late as June, 1930. the Sec\nretary of Agriculture made the state\nment that the unemployment was sea\nsonal and there was relatively no dis\ntress. And further than that, the Sec\nretary of Labor gave out figures with\nrespect to unemployment which were\nshown to be false by the statistics\ngathered by the Department of Labor\nin the State of New York/\u2019\nThe former Governor said he did\nnot take \"the position of placing upon\nthe Republican party the blame for\nthe business depression and consequent\nunemployment, but we do seriously in\ndict them for misleading the people\ninto the belief that a continuance of\nthe Republican party in power meant\ncontinued prosperity.\"\n\u201cWhat has happened to the Repub\nlican party in this Instance,\u201d he con\ntinued. \u201cis nothing more or less than\nfalse issues are injected into a cam\nthe result that must be expected when\npaign. Lack of sincerity or even honesty\nbehind a false campaign pledge not\nonly wrecks itself, but tends to bring\nabout the destruction of those who is\nsue It.\u201d\nG. 0. P. CONGRESS 1\nURGED BY MELLON'\nSecretary Asks United Sup\nport of President in i\nTime of Stress. 11\n\nt\nBy the Associated Press.\nSecretary Mellon last night emerged j\nfrom his customary political silence to i\nask the voters to elect, next Tuesday, a\nRepublican Congress.\n\u201cIt is not time for divided authority,\u201d\nthe Treasury chief told a Nation-wide\nradio audience. \u201cIt is rather a time\nfor strong and united action and. in\nasking support for the President and\nthe administration. I do so In the belief\nthat in this way we shall attain most\nquickly that full measure of economic\nrecovery which is inevitable in a Nation\nso self-reliant and so justifiably con\nfident of the future.\u201d\nEfforts of Administration. I\nThe Secretary said the administration\nwas doing all possible to hasten re-\ncovery from the business depression and\nalleviate suffering from unemployment,\nbut he cautioned his listeners;\n\u201cIt cannot work miracles. The most i\nthat any administration can do is to\nkeep the boat steady and headed in the\nright direction until the storm blows\nover; and that the President has shown\nhe is well able to do.\u201d\nMellon was equally conservative In\ndiscussing the ecoitomic future, assert\ning no one could predict how long it\nwould take to recover from the de\npression.\n\"But of one thing we can be cer\ntain.\u201d he said. \u201cWith our great Inter\nnal organization, our vast resources, our\nunparalleled domestic buying power and\nthe indomitable spirit of our people, we\nshall be among the first of all the na\ntions to recover and resume the onward\nmarch of progress.\u201d\nAnalyzing the depression, both In\nthis country and abroad, the Secretary\nsaid it was not caused by speculation\nin stocks, \u201cthough that was a factor,\nof course, in the situation.\u201d\nOverproduction World-Wide.\nIts underlying causes, he said, were\ntraceable primarily to world-wide over\nproduction, especially of raw materials,\nwnich climaxed a 10-year effort to\ncatch up with the shortages created by\nthe four years of World War.\nMellon was strong in his praise of\nPresident Hoover.\n\u201cPresident Hoover has shown himself\na man capable of dealing with great\nemergencies,\u201d he said. \u201cI am confident\nthat he will lead the country out of\nits present difficulties; but if he is to\ndo so with a minimum of friction and\nloss of time, his hands should not be\ntied by a Congress controlled by his\npolitical opponents.\u201d\nCOOLIDGE WILL ADDRESS\nMASSACHUSETTS VOTERS\nFormer President Refuses Nation-\nWide Broadcast, in Aiding\nButler\u2019s Campaign.\nB.v the Associated Press.\nSPRINGFIELD. Mass.. October 30\nThe high spot of the Republican cam- j\npaign In Massachusetts was scheduled\nfor tonight, when former President Cal- 1\nvin Ccolidg? will break his political\nsilence with his only radio speech of\nthe Fall.\nMr. Coolidge will speak for 15 min- i\nutes over stations WBZ-WBZA, start\ning at 8:30 o'clock. A Nation-wide hook\nup was refused by the former Presi\ndent, who said that his speech was of\ninterest chiefly to the Massachusetts\nvoters.\nHe will speak in the interests of Wil\nliam M. Butler, Republican senatorial\ncandidate who managed the Coolidge\ncampaign of 1924. and Frank O. Allen,\nwho seeks a second term as governor.\nPOSTAL AIDS THEATERS\nNEW YORK, October 30 (A*). \u2014The\nLeague of New York Theaters, formed\nto restrain speculation in theater tick\nets. entered into/a contract Tuesday\nwith the Postal Telegraph Co. for the\ndistribution of pasteboards through all\nits offices.\nThe action followed the resignation\nfrom the league of 16 ticket brokers\nas the result of a dispute over the dis\ntribution of tickets.\nThe new plan provides that the Postal\nCo. may charge 50 cents above bdx j\noffice prices for its service. i\nWASHINGTON'S FINEST MEN'S WEAR STORE\u2014\u2014\"\nRALEIGH HABERDASHER\n1310 F Street\ntBUY NOW\nThe quality is higher\nthe prices loiver on\nTOPCOATS .1\nfor chilly days and\n$295\u00b0\nTailored by Hart Schaffner Marx\nWhen you purchase Topcoats\nlike these, tailored by Hart\nSchaffner Marx, at $29.50, your\nmoney has done a real job. Good\nlooking Scotch tweeds, herring\nbones and cheviots smartly\nstyled and tailored with a deep\nyoke silk lining.\nV**\nMU\nr\ni\ns\n\n\u25a0J\n.'Jf\nt*\nFREE PARKING\u2014at the Capital Garage While Shopping Here\nm\nFESS CONFIDENT\nOF U. S. RESOURCES\nDeclares Exaggerations by\nDemocratic Leaders Partly\nResponsible for Depression.\nBy the Associated Press.\nLIMA, Ohio, October 30. \u2014Senator\nSimeon D. Fess. chairman of the Re\ni publican National Committee, speaking\nat a Republican rally here last night,\ni expressed confidence In the Nation's\nresources and declared that exaggera\ntions by partisan leaders were partly\nresponsible for continued business de\npression.\n\"If carping critics would withhold\ntheir direful prognostications,\" Fess\nsaid, \"if the desire for quick and large\nreturns In the field of speculation would j\ngive way to that of honest Investment l\nand if the partisan leaders would be\nsatisfied to stay within the facts in\nstead of employing exaggerations, quite\na different situation would present it\nself.\u201d\nFe r said the country\u2019s banking re\nsources are abundant and that the sig\nnlflcant barometer of buying power still\nis present In the form of individual\nbank deposits and activities of building\nand loan associations.\nThe Senator said the credit system is\nsoupd. manufacturing plants are intact.j\nnational production is one-third of the j\ni world\u2019s production and we consume 90\nper cent of it at home. Organisations\nfor production and distribution are in\nsome ways stronger than two yean ago, 1 1\nHe said the worker is co-operating in h;\nthe present situation without making I\nundue demands and with no strike\nthreats. This alone, he added, repre\nsents -an achievement which records\na notable chapter in economic history, j\nj It strikes a high note in the states-\ni manship of cur time and augurs much\ni for the well-being of our country.\u201d\nDoctor of Atheism to Be Conferred.\nLENINGRAD. October 30 (JP).\u2014 After\ntwo years\u2019 study graduates of an anti\nreligious university opened recently will\nreceive the degree of doctor of atheism.\nNearly half the 600 students are girls.\n\nMussolini Lauds Father of 32.\nBUSTO. Italy. October 30 (JP).\u2014\nGiovanni Rossi, stone cutter, has re\nceived compliments from Mussolini, in\na personal letter. He is the father of\n32 children.\n\nSpecializing in\ny Perfect\nDIAMONDS X\n4% Also complete line of stand- 4%\nard and all-American made\nwatches. o\nI Shop at the friendly store\u2014 4\nV you\u2019re always greeted with a V\ni 4*4 smile \u2014with no obligation to 4*4\nbuy. T\n\u26664* Charge Accounte Invited *4*\nM. Wurtzburger Co.\nv 901 G St. N.W.\nA-5","height":"25521","width":"19734"}}
